@node Introduction "Introduction"

@{b}What is it ?@{ub}

	This program emulates an HP11C calculator. Everything is there, including
	the program mode. This version is an OS4 port of the original and slightly
	differently named hp11.lha found on Aminet.


@{b}Why Port HP11 ?@{ub}

	You may be asking yourself, why bother porting a calculator to OS4. Surely
	a 68k one would run just as fast. A fair point, there is no real speed gain
	in using a calculator and the PPC executable is also a lot bigger than the
	68k equivalent.

	However, the HP11 programme was showing signs of its age, the GUI did not
	look right under OS4 (nor on OS3 using things like Visual Prefs and screen
	fonts other than topaz 8. The appicon was awful and the cut and paste seemed
	not to work properly either.

	The @{b}main@{ub} reason to port HP11C was as exercise in converting some old code to
	OS4 and be a learning process. If it also makes a much nicer version to run
	on my WB then who is to complain :-)


@{b}Why HP11C with its "strange" RPN notation, surely WB has a calculator ?@{ub}

	Well the Workbench calculator is so basic and is on a par with the one included
	in Windows for usefulness. No others I have ever seen are much better and all
	use arithmetic logic rather than Reverse Polish.

	In the 70s and 80s any @{i}serious@{ui} calculator worth its salt was RPN, from
	my first Prinztronic programmable through to several HP calculators, they are
	the only ones I ever used. RPN at first sight seems an odd way of doing things
	but once you have used it you @{i}never@{ui} want to use an arithmetic type calculator
	again. When confronted with a "normal" calculator I usually revert to pen and
	paper as its quicker than fiddling about looking for equals buttons.

	I also used to have an HP11C calculator for real so was delighted when I found
	the old v1.1 of HP11C several years ago on Aminet. I now cannot do without it,
	even with the old rather constricted GUI of the	68k versions. As the calculator
	came with source code I decided to have a go and do my first Amiga OS4 project.

	@{fg shine}@{b}So for better or worse here is HP11C and it is here to stay for OS4@{ub}@{fg text}

@endnode
@node Usage "Usage"

@{b}Usage@{ub}

	You can pass a filename of a saved state as argument  from CLI, type
	hp11 <path:name>. This may contain an HP11C program or just be a different set
	of conditions such as the display mode or whether calculations are in
	degrees or radians.

	From the Workbench click on the program's icon, press & hold shift and double
	click on the hp11's icon or just double click the program's icon which will
	have the full path of HP11C as the default tool.

	Basically, the program opens a window containing an image of an HP11C in
	either a black image or a white image, depending on which of the executables
	you prefer to use.

	You select keys with the mouse or if you prefer a few are supported by the keyboard.
	The following keys are supported:

	0 - 9		The numeric keys
	.		The decimal point (regardless of how it is displayed . or ,)
	+ - / *		The basic plus, minus, divide and multiply operators.
	^		The y^x key, eg raise the x value to the power x
	_ (underscore)	The CHS (change sign) key.
	Return/Enter	The Enter key on the HP11C
	BackSpace	The left pointing arrow key, which erases characters if
			typing or clear the whole entry if already entered.
	f		The f function key
	g		The g function key
	s		The SIN key
	c		The COS key
	t		The TAN key.
	Esc		The HP11C ON key


	The ON key is treated specially: when you select it, the HP11C becomes an
	icon that you can move around with the mouse. To turn the calculator back
	on, double-click on the icon.

The following menu options are avalaible:

@{fg fill}Project@{fg text}
	Reset			Clear HP11 memory
	Open		RA O	Load an HP11 saved state
	Save		RA S	Save the current HP11C state and/or program  under current name
	Save As		RA A	Save program under a name of your choice
	About		RA ?	Displays some information about HP11C and the current version
	Iconify		RA I	Iconifies the HP11C application
	Quit		RA Q	End program

@{fg fill}Edit@{fg text}
	Copy		RA C	Copy number in display to clipboard
	Paste		RA V	Enter clipboard as a number into X

@{fg fill}Options@{fg text}
	Radix
		Point    RA .	Select UK/USA format for numbers
		Comma    RA ,	Select European format for numbers
	Speed
	Slow			Program's execute at HP11C speed
	Fast			Program's execute faster ...
	Icons			Save an icon with a program ? Default = Off when
				called from CLI, on from Workbench


@{"Using an HP11C" link "Quick"}	This is a very small tutorial for those who don't know how to use an HP11
		and taken without any changes from the original version.


@endnode
@node Quick "Quick"

This is a very small tutorial for those who don't know how to use an HP11:

- The HP11 uses RPN (Reverse Polish Notation), not conventional algebraic
  notation. Calculations must thus be done by first entering the operands,
  and then the operation. For example, to calculate:

    5 + 3	     you type	   5 3 +
    5 * (2 + 4)      you type      5 2 4 + *
    2 * sin(0.5)     you type      0.5 sin 2 *

- When you want to enter two numbers consecutively, you must separate them by
  typing the ENTER key, the above will thus actually be

    5 ENTER 3 +
    5 ENTER 2 ENTER 4 + *
    0.5 SIN 2 * 	     <- ENTER only necessary when entering two numbers

- Intermediate results are saved on a stack, but as this is only 4 levels deep,
  you must be slightly careful in which order you do the operations, as in:

  ( 6 + 5) * (3 + 2 + 4 + 6)

  if you try

  6 ENTER 5 +	3 ENTER 2 ENTER 4 ENTER 6 + + +   *

  you won't get the expected result, because the 11 (result of 6 5 +) will
  have been lost. This is what happens (X, Y, Z, T are the names of the four
  levels of the stack, the keys pressed are marked between the snapshots of
  the stack) :

     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 T   |	   |	   |	 |     |     |	   |	 |     |     |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 Z   |	   |	   |	 |     |     |	   |	 |     |     |
     -------  ENT  -------  5  -------	+  -------  3  -------	ENT
 Y   |	   |	   |  6  |     |  6  |	   |	 |     |  11 |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 X   |	6  |	   |  6  |     |  5  |	   |  11 |     |  3  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------

     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 T   |	   |	   |	 |     |  11 |	   |  11 |     |  3  |	 <- 11 is lost
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 Z   | 11  |	   | 11  |     |   3 |	   |   3 |     |  2  |
     -------   2   ------- ENT -------	4  ------- ENT -------	 6
 Y   |	3  |	   |  3  |     |   2 |	   |   2 |     |  4  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 X   |	3  |	   |  2  |     |   2 |	   |   4 |     |  4  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------

     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 T   |	3  |	   |   3 |     |  3  |	   |  3  |     |  3  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 Z   |	2  |	   |   3 |     |  3  |	   |  3  |     |  3  |
     -------   +   -------  +  -------	+  -------  *  -------
 Y   |	4  |	   |   2 |     |  3  |	   |  3  |     |  3  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------
 X   |	6  |	   |  10 |     | 12  |	   | 15  |     | 45  |
     -------	   -------     -------	   -------     -------


   you get 45 instead of 165 ... You can notice here the effect of ENTER:
   it duplicates the number in X into Y, but the next number entered will
   overwrite it.

   If you had done

   3 ENTER 2 + 4 + 6 +	 6 ENTER 5 + *

   you would have got 165 as expected (it's also shorter to type it this
   way ...). Note that in practice, this problem rarely arises.

- Operations like sin, cos, hyperbolic sine (got by typing f HYP SIN) modify
  the number in X.

- There are 20 registers, accessible by RCL/STO 0-9 & RCL/STO . 0-9

- You can choose the display mode with f FIX/SCI/ENG 0-9, and the angular
  mode with g DEG/RAD/GRAD.

- Statistics use registers 0 to 5 (clear them first with f CLEAR-Sigma).
  Sigma-+ adds the X,Y pair, you can calculate the mean, sdev, linear
  regression, estimation & correlation (these last two simultaneously).

Programming
-----------

- You enter or leave programming mode by typing g P/R.

- You add instructions by typing them, remove them with <-, and you can move
  around in the program with SST, g BST & GTO . xxx, where xxx is the
  program step number.

- Programs are composed of numbered steps, from 1 to 203. When a program is
  run, these are normally executed sequentially.

- Program steps are displayed as sequences of up to 3 pairs of 2 digits
  (eventually with a . ) These numbers correspond to the keys pressed to
  enter the instructions, with the keys numbered starting at 11 for
  square root, 12 for e^x, ... 16 for CHS, 10 for /, 21 for SST, ...
  Digits (0 to 9) are represented as themselves. Experiment ! You'll
  remember them after a while (if you have the patience :-)).

- Gotos: You can enter labels anywhere, with f LBL 0-9 or A-E. GTO 0-9, A-E
  will transfer control to the step following the label.
@endnode
@node Future "Future"
	@{b}Future Development@{ub}


		1. Fix any known bugs or as yet to be discovered ones.


		2. Add the ability to allow the calculator to jump to other
		public screens.  This would most likely be a menu item.
		

		3. If I can ever find an HP11C manual, provide more information
		about using the programmable side of the calculator.


		4. The GUI image is a bit small for modern screenmodes. This
		could be made from a larger image - unfortunately I am no artist.


		5. Related to item 4.  Allow the use of datatypes to load any valid
		image format for the GUI.


@endnode
@node WhatsNew "What's New for version 1.3"
@{b}What's New for version 1.3@{ub}

	HP11C is now a native OS4 application.

	@{b}GUI@{ub}
	
	Older versions of HP11 assumed that Topaz 8 was used for the screen font and that window
	borders would be of a fixed size and nothing else. If any other size font is used or any
	Visual Prefs type hacks alter the border sizes then the HP11 GUI was corrupted by the
	window borders. Now the window is font and GUI sensitive.

	The window will now never open covering the title bar even after being iconified.
	By default the window opens just below the title bar and 10 pixels from the
	left of the screen, tooltypes may later be added to choose the opening position.

	HP11 v1.1 had an image that was black text on a white background. HP11 v1.2 was
	white text on black (maybe more realistic but harder to read IMHO. HP11C v1.3
	is available as two choices of executable one white on black, one black on white,
	the user can choose which they prefer. Like v1.2, there is no need for an extra
	file HP11.pic as the data is contained in the executable.

	@{b}Starting HP11C@{ub}  From v1.2 you can start HP11C with a specific register state either
	from clicking a saved state icon or specifying the name of a saved state in the shell
	command. However icons could only be saved in the same directory as HP11C. Now it is
	possible to save the saved state project icons anywhere as the full path to HP11C is
	saved as the default tool.

	@{b}Menus@{ub}

	Uses gadtools and new look menus as in version 1.2.
	Corrected usage of checkbox since v1.2 for the Icons option.
	Added About and Iconify options in the Project Menu.
	Renamed the Project -> New option to Project -> Reset as it makes far more sense.

	@{b}Clipboard@{ub}

	The clipboard did not work properly in either v1.1 nor v1.2. Version 1.2 could cut
	and paste within the calculator but not between other applications. It is now possible
	to cut and paste numbers between HP11C and other applications. This is still not 100%
	perfect see @{"Known Bugs" link "Bugs"}.


	@{b}Project Icons and Appicon@{ub}

	Gone are the hard coded WB1.3 style icons from v1.1, and the oddly implemented
	iconified icon that draws all over your WB screen.  Version 1.2 worked better but
	lost its images and only used default WB icon images. Also the saved state icons did
	not include the path to HP11C so if you saved an HP11C configuration anywhere other
	than the same directory as HP11 then clicking the icon would not find HP11.

	Now the saved state icons can be saved anywhere and launch HP11C from a double click.

	The appicon and project icons use the HP11C icon image and if this fails fall back to
	a default WB Tool or WB Project icon accordingly - see @{"Known Bugs" link "Bugs"}.

	Furthermore the user can use their own icons instead of using the HP11C icon. If a
	file envarc:sys/def_HP11C.info exists this will be used for the saved project icon
	and the appicon. Further to this if a file envarc:sys/def_HP11appicon.info exists then
	this will be used for the iconified appicon.




@endnode
@node Bugs "Known Bugs"
@{b}@{fg shine}Known Bugs@{fg text}@{ub}

	@{b}Clipboard@{ub}     Cutting and pasting numbers between HP11C and other applications works
	with most applications I have tested. I have been informed that there is a problem
	between HP11C and Final Writer. If anyone finds any other clipping and pasting
	problems then please let @{"me" link "Author"} know.

	@{b}Finding the Icon@{ub}    If HP11C is in the default AmigaOS path (eg. Sys:Tools) and is
	started from the shell by simply typing "HP11C" without a full path, then HP11C will 
	run but not be able to find its own icon. Any other method of starting HP11C will have 
	no such issue. This bug is not considered serious for the following reasons.

		When starting from the shell HP11C defaults to saving programme states without 
		icons, however the appicon will be affected.

		If no icon image can be found then the default WB Project icon is used for 
		the saved state icon and the default WB Tool icon used for the appicon.

		If there exist in Envarc:sys def_HP11C,info and/or def_HP11Cappicon.info then 
		these will be used for the saved state icons and the iconified appicon.

	@{b}Prefix@{ub}    One function on the HP11C uses the @{fg fill}f@{fg text} key followed by the @{fg fill}Prefix@{fg text}
	key. In older versions this used a Unix function not available to GCC. As I have no 
	HP11C manual and do not know what this function is meant to do, it is currently 
	disabled and just displays zeros.


@endnode
@node History "History"
Insert text here


Version 1.3

	This version is a PPC conversion and will only run on Amiga OS4.
	Older 68k versions are still available on Aminet.

	Changed name from HP11.lha to HP11C.lha to avoid any accidental
	replacement of older 68k versions on Aminet.

	For more details see @{" What's New for 1.3     " link "WhatsNew"}.
@endnode
@node Installation "Installing HP11C"
	@{b}Installation@{ub}

		No installer is required, simply copy HP11C (and its icon) to
		anywhere you wish on your system. Sys:Tools would be an
		appropriate suggestion.

		Note: there are two HP11C executables, if you wish the black look,
		then copy HP11C.black instead then rename it to HP11C.

		Then copy this Guide to where you keep your documentation
		files. eg. Help:  Copy the file HP11.png to the same location.



		Also the icons drawer contains a couple of example icons that can
		be used for HP11C or as def_icons for HP11C projects or the
		iconified state. These are optional, but if you want any of them copy
		them to Envarc:sys
@endnode
